This gene is involved in the regulation of gene expression that modulates cell motility.

The human MIR135B wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 1q32.1 and is approximately 97 bases in length. This allele, which encodes MIR135B pre-miRNA, plays a role in the regulation of gene expression. Alteration in the expression of this gene is associated with highly invasive non-small-cell lung cancer.
MIR135B pre-miRNA (97 nucleotides) is encoded by the human MIR135B gene. This oligoribonucleotide is involved in the regulation of gene expression.
This gene plays a role in angiogenesis.

Human TNFSF12 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 17p13 and is approximately 13 kb in length. This allele, which encodes tumor necrosis factor ligand superfamily member 12 protein, is involved in the promotion of angiogenesis. A readthrough that fuses this gene and the neighboring TNFSF13 gene may be expressed in activated T-cells and T- or B-cell lymphoma.

label.value: Tumor Necrosis Factor Ligand Superfamily Member 12

value.value: Tumor necrosis factor ligand superfamily member 12 (249 aa, ~27 kDa) is encoded by the human TNFSF12 gene. This protein plays a role in the positive regulation of angiogenesis.
A seizure triggered by a migraine.
A headache associated with muscle tightness which may radiate to other parts of the body.
This gene is involved in signal transduction and the promotion of angiogenesis.

Human TNFRSF12A wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 16p13.3 and is approximately 4 kb in length. This allele, which encodes tumor necrosis factor receptor superfamily member 12A protein, plays a role in the modulation of both angiogenesis and apoptosis.

label.value: Tumor Necrosis Factor Receptor Superfamily Member 12A

value.value: Tumor necrosis factor receptor superfamily member 12A (129 aa, ~14 kDa) is encoded by the human TNFRSF12A gene. This protein is involved in both apoptosis and angiogenesis.
A headache disorder characterized by episodes of unilateral, short lasting pain and associated ipsilateral cranial autonomic symptoms.
This gene plays a role in cell adhesion in hematopoietic cells.

Human FERMT3 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 11q13.1 and is approximately 17 kb in length. This allele, which encodes fermitin family homolog 3 protein, is involved in the modulation of cell adhesion. Mutation of the gene is associated with leukocyte adhesion deficiency-3.
A headache disorder that is characterized by periodic severe, unilateral orbital, supraorbital, and/or temporal pain, and is associated with ipsilateral cranial autonomic symptoms.
Headache triggered by coughing or straining in the absence of an intracranial disorder.
Headache triggered by exercise.
Fermitin family homolog 3 (667 aa, ~76 kDa) is encoded by the human FERMT3 gene. This protein plays a role in hematopoietic cell adhesion, migration and proliferation.

A unilateral headache of moderate intensity with exacerbations of severe pain, not attributed to another disorder, that continuously persists for more than three months, and presents with ipsilateral autonomic symptoms during exacerbations.
A bilateral, unremitting headache of mild to moderate intensity that occurs daily and may be associated with photophobia, phonophobia, or mild nausea.
Headache resulting from pressure applied to the cutaneous nerves of the head.
Pain that occurs after the disappearance of herpes zoster infection lesions.
This gene is involved in the modulation of cytokine expression and B- and T-cell activities.

Human IL27 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 16p11 and is approximately 13 kb in length. This allele, which encodes interleukin-27 subunit alpha protein, plays a role in the stimulation of innate immunity.
Interleukin-27 subunit alpha (243 aa, ~27 kDa) is encoded by the human IL27 gene. This protein is involved in the modulation of angiogenesis, inflammation and tumorigenesis.
This gene plays a role in innate immunity.

Human EBI3 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 19p13.3 and is approximately 8 kb in length. This allele, which encodes interleukin-27 subunit beta protein, is involved in the regulation of inflammation, tumorigenesis and angiogenesis.
